[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:dlss-upscaling/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] All generations of DLSS are available on all RTX-branded cards from Nvidia in supported titles.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] However, the Frame Generation feature is only supported on RTX 40 series GPUs or newer and Multi Frame Generation is only available on 50 series GPUs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia advertised DLSS as a key feature of GeForce RTX 20 series GPUs when they launched in September 2018.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] At that time, the results were limited to a few video games, namely *Battlefield V*, or *Metro Exodus*, because the algorithm had to be trained specifically on each game on which it was applied and the results were usually not as good as simple resolution upscaling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] In 2019, *Control* shipped with ray tracing and an image processing algorithm that approximated DLSS, which did not use the Tensor Cores.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] In April 2020, Nvidia advertised and shipped an improved version of DLSS named DLSS 2 with driver version 445.75.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 2.0 was available for a few existing games including *Control* and *Wolfenstein: Youngblood*, and would later be added to many newly released games and game engines such as Unreal Engine and Unity.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] This time Nvidia said that it used the Tensor Cores again, and that the AI did not need to be trained specifically on each game.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Despite sharing the DLSS branding, the two iterations of DLSS differ significantly and are not backwards-compatible.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] In January 2025, Nvidia stated that there are over 540 games and apps supporting DLSS, and that over 80% of Nvidia RTX users activate DLSS.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] In March 2025, there were more than 100 games that support DLSS 4, according to Nvidia.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] By May 2025, over 125 games supported DLSS 4.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The first video game console to use DLSS, the Nintendo Switch 2, was released on June 5, 2025.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] In January 2026, Nvidia stated that over 250 games and applications support Multi Frame Generation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] On March 16, 2026, at GTC 2026, Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang presented DLSS 5, a real-time AI model based on neural rendering that realistically enhances lighting and material surfaces at up to 4K resolution while retaining the developer's intended art style.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] It is planned to release in fall of 2026.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] In a blog post on its website, Nvidia has announced that DLSS 5 will be available in such games as *Assassin's Creed Shadows*, *Delta Force*, *Hogwarts Legacy*, *Naraka: Bladepoint*, *Phantom Blade Zero*, *Resident Evil Requiem*, *Starfield*, *The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion Remastered*, and more.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] On May 31, 2026, Nvidia announced an updated version of Ray Reconstruction for DLSS 4.5 in a blog post, scheduled for release on all RTX GPUs in August of the same year.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] They said it is designed to better embed spatial awareness into scenes and analyze engine data on movements and lighting conditions, resulting in a sharper, more stable, and less noisy image.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The first iteration of DLSS is a predominantly spatial image upscaler with two stages, both relying on convolutional auto-encoder neural networks.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The first step is an image enhancement network which uses the current frame and motion vectors to perform edge enhancement, and spatial anti-aliasing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The second stage is an image upscaling step which uses the single raw, low-resolution frame to upscale the image to the desired output resolution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Using just a single frame for upscaling means the neural network itself must generate a large amount of new information to produce the high-resolution output, which can result in slight hallucinations such as leaves that differ in style to the source content.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The neural networks are trained on a per-game basis by generating a "perfect frame" using traditional supersampling to 64 samples per pixel, as well as the motion vectors for each frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The data collected must be as comprehensive as possible, including as many levels, times of day, graphical settings, resolutions, etc. as possible.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] This data is also augmented using common augmentations such as rotations, colour changes, and random noise to help generalize the test data.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Training is performed on Nvidia's Saturn V supercomputer.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia also demonstrated the ability for the auto-encoder networks to learn the ability to recreate depth-of-field and motion blur, although this functionality has never been included in a publicly released product.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 2 is a temporal anti-aliasing upsampling (TAAU) implementation, using data from previous frames extensively through sub-pixel jittering to resolve fine detail and reduce aliasing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The data DLSS 2 collects includes: the raw low-resolution input, motion vectors, depth buffers, and exposure / brightness information.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] It can also be used as a simpler TAA implementation where the image is rendered at 100% resolution, rather than being upsampled by DLSS, Nvidia brands this as DLAA (Deep Learning Anti-Aliasing).
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] TAA(U) is used in many modern video games and game engines; however, all previous implementations have used some form of manually written heuristics to prevent temporal artifacts such as ghosting and flickering.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] One example of this is neighborhood clamping which forcefully prevents samples collected in previous frames from deviating too much compared to nearby pixels in newer frames.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] This helps to identify and fix many temporal artifacts, but deliberately removing fine details in this way is analogous to applying a blur filter, and thus the final image can appear blurry when using this method.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 2 uses a convolutional auto-encoder neural network trained to identify and fix temporal artifacts, instead of manually programmed heuristics as mentioned above.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Because of this, DLSS 2 can generally resolve detail better than other TAA and TAAU implementations, while also removing most temporal artifacts.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] This is why DLSS 2 can sometimes produce a sharper image than rendering at higher, or even native resolutions using traditional TAA.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] However, no temporal solution is perfect, and artifacts (ghosting in particular) are still visible in some scenarios when using DLSS 2.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Because temporal artifacts occur in most art styles and environments in broadly the same way, the neural network that powers DLSS 2 does not need to be retrained when being used in different games.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Despite this, Nvidia does frequently ship new minor revisions of DLSS 2 with new titles, so this could suggest some minor training optimizations may be performed as games are released, although Nvidia does not provide changelogs for these minor revisions to confirm this.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The main advancements compared to DLSS 1 include: Significantly improved detail retention, a generalized neural network that does not need to be re-trained per-game, and ~2x less overhead (~1–2 ms vs ~2–4 ms).
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] It should also be noted that forms of TAAU such as DLSS 2 are not upscalers in the same sense as techniques such as ESRGAN or DLSS 1, which attempt to create new information from a low-resolution source; instead, TAAU works to recover data from previous frames, rather than creating new data.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] In practice, this means low resolution textures in games will still appear low-resolution when using current TAAU techniques.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] This is why Nvidia recommends game developers use higher resolution textures than they would normally for a given rendering resolution by applying a mip-map bias when DLSS 2 is enabled.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Augments DLSS 2 with improved image quality and the introduction of a new motion interpolation feature, called Frame Generation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The DLSS Frame Generation algorithm takes two rendered frames from the rendering pipeline and generates a new frame that smoothly transitions between them.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] For every frame rendered, one additional frame is generated.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 3.0 makes use of a new generation Optical Flow Accelerator (OFA) included in the Ada Lovelace architecture of GeForce RTX 40 series GPUs and with that is exclusive to them.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The new OFA is said to be faster and more accurate than the one already available in previous Turing and Ampere RTX GPUs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 3.5 adds Ray Reconstruction, replacing multiple denoising algorithms with a single AI model trained on five times more data than DLSS 3.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Ray Reconstruction is available on all RTX GPUs and first targeted games with path tracing (aka "full ray tracing"), including *Cyberpunk 2077'*s *Phantom Liberty* DLC, *Portal with RTX*, and *Alan Wake 2*.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The fourth generation of DLSS was unveiled alongside the GeForce RTX 50 series.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 4 upscaling uses a new vision transformer-based model for enhanced image quality with reduced ghosting and greater image stability in motion compared to the previous convolutional neural network (CNN) model.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 4 allows a greater number of frames to be generated and interpolated based on a single traditionally rendered frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] This form of frame generation called Multi Frame Generation is exclusive to the GeForce RTX 50 series while the GeForce RTX 40 series is limited to one interpolated frame per traditionally rendered frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia claims that DLSS 4x Frame Generation model uses 30% less video memory with the example of *Warhammer 40,000: Darktide* using 400MB less memory at 4K resolution with Frame Generation enabled.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia claims that 75 games will integrate DLSS 4 Multi Frame Generation at launch, including *Alan Wake 2*, *Cyberpunk 2077*, *Indiana Jones and the Great Circle*, and *Star Wars Outlaws*.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 4.5 introduces Dynamic Multi Frame Generation, which can dynamically generate up to 6x the amount of frames for GeForce RTX 50-series GPUs, and upgrades the transformer model used for upscaling to a second-generation model for better temporal stability, ghosting and anti-aliasing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS 5, announced at GTC 2026, uses a neural rendering-based AI model to enhance lighting and material surfaces in real time at up to 4K resolution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia described the technology as retaining the developer's intended art style, while using color and motion-vector data to generate temporally stable lighting and material effects.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS requires and applies its own anti-aliasing method.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Thus, depending on the game and quality setting used, using DLSS may improve image quality even over native resolution rendering.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] It operates on similar principles to TAA.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Like TAA, it uses information from past frames to produce the current frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Unlike TAA, DLSS does not sample every pixel in every frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Instead, it samples different pixels in different frames and uses pixels sampled in past frames to fill in the unsampled pixels in the current frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS uses machine learning to combine samples in the current frame and past frames, and is made possible by the available tensor cores.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Nvidia also offers Deep Learning Anti-Aliasing (DLAA), which provides the same AI-driven anti-aliasing DLSS uses, but without any upscaling or downscaling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] With the exception of the shader-core version implemented in *Control*, DLSS is only available on GeForce RTX 20, GeForce RTX 30, GeForce RTX 40, GeForce RTX 50, and Quadro RTX series of video cards, using dedicated AI accelerators called **Tensor Cores**.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Tensor Cores are available since the Nvidia Volta GPU microarchitecture, which was first used on the Tesla V100 line of products.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] They are used for doing fused multiply-add (FMA) operations that are used extensively in neural network calculations for applying a large series of multiplications on weights, followed by the addition of a bias.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Tensor cores can operate on FP16, INT8, INT4, and INT1 data types.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Each core can do 1024 bits of FMA operations per clock, so 1024 INT1, 256 INT4, 128 INT8, and 64 FP16 operations per clock per tensor core, and most Turing GPUs have a few hundred tensor cores.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The Tensor Cores use CUDA Warp-Level Primitives on 32 parallel threads to take advantage of their parallel architecture.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] A Warp is a set of 32 threads which are configured to execute the same instruction.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Since Windows 10 version 1903, Microsoft provided DirectML as one part of DirectX to support Tensor Cores.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The linear scale factor used for upsampling the input resolution to the output resolution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] For example, a scene rendered at 540p with a 2.00x scale factor would have an output resolution of 1080p.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The linear render scale, compared to the output resolution, that the technology uses to render scenes internally before upsampling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] For example, a 1080p scene with a 50% render scale would have an internal resolution of 540p.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Users can manually replace the DLLs in games to support a newer version of DLSS.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] DLSS Swapper, an open source utility, can automatically do this for all installed games.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Replacing DLL files can not add DLSS support or features to games that do not already implement them, though some mods can add frame generation support.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] It is also possible to override the DLSS version without touching game files via the Nvidia App.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] While the Nvidia App does not specify the DLSS version used in each preset available, the following table summarizes this information.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Particularly in early versions of DLSS, users reported blurry frames.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Andrew Edelsten, an employee at Nvidia, therefore commented on the problem in a blog post in 2019 and promised that they were working on improving the technology and clarified that the DLSS AI algorithm was mainly trained with 4K image material.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] That the use of DLSS leads to particularly blurred images at lower resolutions, such as Full HD, is due to the fact that the algorithm has far less image information available to calculate an appropriate image compared to higher resolutions like 4K.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The use of DLSS Frame Generation leads to increased input latency, as well as visual artifacts.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] It has also been criticized that by implementing DLSS in their games, game developers no longer have an incentive to optimize them so that they also run smoothly in native resolution on modern PC hardware.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] For example, for the game *Alan Wake 2* in 4K at the highest graphics settings with ray tracing enabled, the use of DLSS in Performance mode is recommended even with graphics cards such as the Nvidia GeForce RTX 4080 in order to achieve 60 fps.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Upon its announcement at GTC 2026, DLSS 5 received significant backlash from both gamers and game developers on social media.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] Critics argued that the technology's neural rendering-based approach altered games' art direction in ways not intended by their developers, with some comparing its output to AI slop.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] The technology's handling of human faces drew particular criticism.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] *The Verge* highlighted an example from *EA Sports FC 26* in which Liverpool captain Virgil van Dijk's facial features were noticeably distorted by the technology, and compared the overall effect to motion smoothing on televisions.
[src:dlss-upscaling/deep-learning-super-sampling] *IGN* characterized DLSS 5 as undermining the artistic craft of video game design, and *Engadget* argued that the negative reaction from gamers was justified.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] In computer graphics and digital imaging, **image scaling** is the resizing of a digital image.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] In video technology, the magnification of digital material is known as upscaling or resolution enhancement.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] When scaling a vector graphic image, the graphic primitives that make up the image can be rendered using geometric transformations at any resolution with no loss of image quality.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] When scaling a raster graphics image, a new image with a higher or lower number of pixels must be generated.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] In the case of decreasing the pixel number (scaling down), this usually results in a visible quality loss.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] From the standpoint of digital signal processing, the scaling of raster graphics is a two-dimensional example of sample-rate conversion, the conversion of a discrete signal from a sampling rate (in this case, the local sampling rate) to another.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Image scaling can be interpreted as a form of image resampling or image reconstruction from the view of the Nyquist sampling theorem.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] According to the theorem, downsampling to a smaller image from a higher-resolution original can only be carried out after applying a suitable 2D anti-aliasing filter to prevent aliasing artifacts.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] The image is reduced to the information that can be carried by the smaller image.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] In the case of up sampling, a reconstruction filter takes the place of the anti-aliasing filter.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] A more sophisticated approach to upscaling treats the problem as an inverse problem, solving the question of generating a plausible image that, when scaled down, would look like the input image.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] A variety of techniques have been applied for this, including optimization techniques with regularization terms and the use of machine learning from examples.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] An image size can be changed in several ways.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] One of the simpler ways of increasing image size is nearest-neighbor interpolation, replacing every pixel with the nearest pixel in the output; for upscaling, this means multiple pixels of the same color will be present.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This can preserve sharp details but also introduce jaggedness in previously smooth images.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] 'Nearest' in nearest-neighbor does not have to be the mathematical nearest.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] One common implementation is to always round toward zero.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Rounding this way produces fewer artifacts and is faster to calculate.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This algorithm is often preferred for images which have little to no smooth edges.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] A common application of this can be found in pixel art.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Bilinear interpolation works by interpolating pixel color values, introducing a continuous transition into the output even where the original material has discrete transitions.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Although this is desirable for continuous-tone images, this algorithm reduces contrast (sharp edges) in a way that may be undesirable for line art.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Bicubic interpolation yields substantially better results, with an increase in computational cost.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Sinc resampling, in theory, provides the best possible reconstruction for a perfectly bandlimited signal.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] In practice, the assumptions behind sinc resampling are not completely met by real-world digital images.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Lanczos resampling, an approximation to the sinc method, yields better results.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Bicubic interpolation can be regarded as a computationally efficient approximation to Lanczos resampling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] One weakness of bilinear, bicubic, and related algorithms is that they sample a specific number of pixels.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] When downscaling below a certain threshold, such as more than twice for all bi-sampling algorithms, the algorithms will sample non-adjacent pixels, which results in both losing data and rough results.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] The trivial solution to this issue is box sampling, which is to consider the target pixel a box on the original image and sample all pixels inside the box.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This ensures that all input pixels contribute to the output.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] The major weakness of this algorithm is that it is hard to optimize.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Another solution to the downscale problem of bi-sampling scaling is mipmaps.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] A mipmap is a prescaled set of downscaled copies.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] When downscaling, the nearest larger mipmap is used as the origin to ensure no scaling below the useful threshold of bilinear scaling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This algorithm is fast and easy to optimize.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] It is standard in many frameworks, such as OpenGL.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] The cost is using more image memory, exactly one-third more in the standard implementation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Simple interpolation based on the Fourier transform pads the frequency domain with zero components (a smooth window-based approach would reduce the ringing).
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Besides the good conservation (or recovery) of details, notable are the ringing and the circular bleeding of content from the left border to the right border (and the other way around).
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Edge-directed interpolation algorithms aim to preserve edges in the image after scaling, unlike other algorithms, which can introduce staircase artifacts.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Examples of algorithms for this task include New Edge-Directed Interpolation (NEDI), Edge-Guided Image Interpolation (EGGI), Iterative Curvature-Based Interpolation (ICBI), and Directional Cubic Convolution Interpolation (DCCI).
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] A 2013 analysis found that DCCI had the best scores in peak signal-to-noise ratio and structural similarity on a series of test images.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] For magnifying computer graphics with low resolution and/or few colors (usually from 2 to 256 colors), better results can be achieved by hqx or other pixel-art scaling algorithms.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] These produce sharp edges and maintain a high level of detail.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Vector extraction, or vectorization, offers another approach.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Vectorization first creates a resolution-independent vector representation of the graphic to be scaled.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] The resulting SVG vector file can then be exported and rendered at any required resolution without quality loss, serving directly as production-ready artwork for scalable display & printing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This technique is used by Adobe Illustrator, Live Trace, and Inkscape.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Scalable Vector Graphics are well suited to simple geometric images, while photographs do not fare well with vectorization due to their complexity.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This method uses machine learning for more detailed images, such as photographs and complex artwork.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Programs that use this method include waifu2x, Imglarger and Neural Enhance.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] AI-driven upscaling software allows detail and sharpness to be added to historical photographs, where it is not present in the original.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] The availability of AI upscaling tools has led to confusion where a person believes that the upscaled version of a blurry image is genuinely showing them the subject of the original photograph.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] In 2025 a user of the social media site X posted an AI-upscaled version of a low resolution photo of Donald Trump that they had zoomed in on, and asked if anyone could "explain what the hell is happening to his forehead".
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Experts noted that the image had been distorted by the upscaling process, and that such tools "inevitably have to invent, or at least recreate, details that were or were not there".
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Image scaling is used in, among other applications, web browsers, image editors, image and file viewers, software magnifiers, digital zoom, the process of generating thumbnail images, and when outputting images through screens or printers.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This application is the magnification of images for home theaters for HDTV-ready output devices from PAL-Resolution content, for example, from a DVD player.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Upscaling is performed in real time, and the output signal is not saved.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] As pixel-art graphics are usually low-resolution, they rely on careful placement of individual pixels, often with a limited palette of colors.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This results in graphics that rely on stylized visual cues to define complex shapes with little resolution, down to individual pixels.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] This makes scaling pixel art a particularly difficult problem.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Specialized algorithms were developed to handle pixel-art graphics, as the traditional scaling algorithms do not take perceptual cues into account.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Since a typical application is to improve the appearance of fourth-generation and earlier video games on arcade and console emulators, many are designed to run in real time for small input images at 60 frames per second.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] On fast hardware, these algorithms are suitable for gaming and other real-time image processing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] These algorithms provide sharp, crisp graphics, while minimizing blur.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Scaling art algorithms have been implemented in a wide range of emulators such as HqMAME and DOSBox, as well as 2D game engines and game engine recreations such as ScummVM.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] They gained recognition with gamers, for whom these technologies encouraged a revival of 1980s and 1990s gaming experiences.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Such filters are currently used in commercial emulators on Xbox Live, Virtual Console, and PSN to allow classic low-resolution games to be more visually appealing on modern HD displays.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Recently released games that incorporate these filters include *Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection*, *Castlevania: The Dracula X Chronicles*, *Castlevania: Symphony of the Night*, and *Akumajō Dracula X Chi no Rondo*.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] A number of companies have developed techniques to upscale video frames in real-time, such as when they are drawn on screen in a video game.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Nvidia's deep learning super sampling (DLSS) uses deep learning to upsample lower-resolution images to a higher resolution for display on higher-resolution computer monitors.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution 1.0 (FSR) does not employ machine learning, instead using traditional hand-written algorithms to achieve spatial upscaling on traditional shading units.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] FSR 2.0 utilises temporal upscaling, again with a hand-tuned algorithm.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] FSR standardized presets are not enforced, and some titles such as *Dota 2* offer resolution sliders.
[src:dlss-upscaling/image-scaling] Other technologies include Intel XeSS and Nvidia Image Scaler (NIS).
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] Aliasing is manifested in the case of 2D images as moiré pattern and pixelated edges, colloquially known as "jaggies".
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] Common signal processing and image processing knowledge suggests that to achieve perfect elimination of aliasing, proper spatial sampling at the Nyquist rate (or higher) after applying a 2D Anti-aliasing filter is required.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] As this approach would require a forward and inverse fourier transformation, computationally less demanding approximations like supersampling were developed to avoid domain switches by staying in the spatial domain ("image domain").
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] Supersampling is computationally expensive because it requires much greater video card memory and memory bandwidth, since the amount of buffer used is several times larger.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] A way around this problem is to use a technique known as **adaptive supersampling**, where only pixels at the edges of objects are supersampled.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] Initially only a few samples are taken within each pixel.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] If these values are very similar, only these samples are used to determine the color.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] The result of this method is that a higher number of samples are calculated only where necessary, thus improving performance.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] When taking samples within a pixel, the sample positions have to be determined in some way.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] Although the number of ways in which this can be done is infinite, there are a few ways which are commonly used.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] The pixel is split into several sub-pixels, and a sample is taken from the center of each.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] Although, due to the regular nature of sampling, aliasing can still occur if a low number of sub-pixels is used.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] Also known as stochastic sampling, it avoids the regularity of grid supersampling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] However, due to the irregularity of the pattern, samples end up being unnecessary in some areas of the pixel and lacking in others.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] The Poisson disk sampling algorithm places the samples randomly, but then checks that any two are not too close.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] The end result is an even but random distribution of samples.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] The naive "dart throwing" algorithm is extremely slow for large data sets, which once limited its applications for real-time rendering.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] However, many fast algorithms now exist to generate Poisson disk noise, even those with variable density.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] The Delone set provides a mathematical description of such sampling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] A modification of the grid algorithm to approximate the Poisson disk.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] A pixel is split into several sub-pixels, but a sample is not taken from the center of each, but from a random point within the sub-pixel.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] Congregation can still occur, but to a lesser degree.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] A 2×2 grid layout is used but the sample pattern is rotated to avoid samples aligning on the horizontal or vertical axis, greatly improving antialiasing quality for the most commonly encountered cases.
[src:dlss-upscaling/supersampling] For an optimal pattern, the rotation angle is arctan (⁠1/2⁠) (about 26.6°) and the square is stretched by a factor of ⁠√5/2⁠, making it also a 4-queens solution.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] The modern definition of TAA is a spatial anti-aliasing technique for real-time computer graphics that reuses information from previously rendered frames to remove aliasing, such as jaggies, from the current frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] The term *temporal anti-aliasing* is somewhat of a misnomer, and this technique is formally referred to as *temporally-amortized supersampling.* It is also known as TXAA (an implementation by Nvidia) or *Temporal Super-Sampling Anti-Aliasing* (TSSAA).
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] This method can achieve results comparable to supersampling, at a small fraction of the computational cost, but produces soft images and can cause ghosting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA popularized in video games in the 2010s, with two early examples being Halo: Reach and Crysis 2, and is now the most common form of spatial anti-aliasing in real-time rendering and game engines.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Each pixel is sampled at a slightly different position each frame, which is achieved by adding a 2D offset to each frame, a "jitter" that shifts the image by a fraction of the size of a pixel, horizontally and vertically.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] The jitter changes each frame, following a pattern (such as a Halton sequence) so that every point in the image is sampled evenly over time.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Old frames are blended into the current frame, accumulating historical rendering data, approaching the result of supersampling over time.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Changes to the scene—such as moving objects, camera motion, or changes in lighting—often mean that the history for any given pixel may be somewhere else on screen, be invalid, or may not exist at all.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Failure to account for these changes results in ghosting.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] To account for movement, velocity vectors are maintained in the G-buffer, allowing the location of each pixel in the previous frame to be calculated.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] The pixel at that location in the previous frame is accumulated into a history buffer, at its new location.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Accurate velocities are required to prevent smearing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Often, the historical data for a pixel will become invalid due to changes in occlusion, such as the pixel having recently become visible after being blocked by an object last frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] This causes ghosting unless it is detected: One method is to compare the depth of the historical position to the depth values in the current pixel's neighborhood.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Color can also be useful for validating the history of a pixel, since a sudden change in color can indicate new lighting conditions or an incorrect pixel velocity.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] A drawback of TAA is that it does not work well with transparent objects, particles, or reflections, because they can produce incorrect velocity vectors.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] In the case of transparency, this is because only one velocity vector can typically be stored per pixel.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Dithering can be used to simulate opacity, a technique known as *screen-door transparency*, which works with TAA and is smoothed out over time by it.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Ghosting and blurriness are two disadvantages specific to TAA, though both can be significantly reduced with proper implementation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA requires more engine- and game-specific tuning than other anti-aliasing methods to achieve acceptable results; poorly-tuned implementations can severely exacerbate TAA's issues in some situations.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Brute force supersampling (rendering at a higher resolution and downsampling), which is considered a gold standard for spatial anti-aliasing, is very costly compared to TAA, which can produce comparable results in many situations.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA), which was previously the most common real-time spatial anti-aliasing method, does not work well with deferred shading, which is needed for a number of common rendering techniques.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Several post-processing anti-aliasing methods were developed to overcome this limitation, such as fast approximate anti-aliasing (FXAA), and morphological anti-aliasing (MLAA).
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] These methods can have poor temporal stability, such as causing flickering artifacts.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] TAA generally reduces aliasing better than these methods, is more temporally stable, and still works with deferred shading.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Deep learning super sampling (DLSS), developed by Nvidia, operates on similar principles to TAA.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] DLSS uses machine learning to combine samples in the current frame and past frames, and it can be thought of as an advanced TAA implementation.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] The traditional definition of TAA is the removal of temporal aliasing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] A photograph collects light over a period of time, called an exposure.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] This can result in moving objects exhibiting motion blur, which is sometimes a desirable effect.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] In computer graphics, images are often rendered at a single instant in time, ignoring the effects of motion, for convenience.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] This results in temporal aliasing: moving objects can appear to jump or flash between frames as their position changes.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] This effect can be mitigated, but not eliminated, by using a higher refresh rate display, and increasing the frame rate to match the refresh rate.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Another approach, analogous to spatial supersampling, is to simulate motion blur by rendering many instants in time, integrating them into each frame.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Aliasing is a result of the sampling theorem of signal processing: To avoid it, a signal must be sampled at a rate at least twice the highest frequency present in the signal.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] An example of temporal aliasing is the wagon-wheel effect, where spinning objects can appear to move slowly, stop, or reverse.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Temporal aliasing can also affect film and video.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] The shutter behavior of the sampling system (the camera) strongly influences aliasing, because the window function of the exposure (its shape over time) determines how well bandlimited the image signal is before sampling.
[src:dlss-upscaling/temporal-anti-aliasing] Different window functions can be chosen to reduce temporal aliasing.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Video scalers are typically found inside consumer electronics devices such as televisions, video game consoles, and DVD or Blu-ray players, but can also be found in other AV equipment (such as video editing and television broadcasting equipment).
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Video scalers can also be completely separate devices, often providing simple video switching capabilities.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] These units are commonly found as part of home theatre or projected presentation systems.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] They are often combined with other video processing devices or algorithms to create a video processor that improves the apparent definition of video signals.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Video scalers are primarily a digital device; however, they can be combined with an analog-to-digital converter (ADC, or digitizer) and a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) to support analog inputs and outputs.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] The native resolution of a display is how many physical pixels make up each row and column of the visible area on the display's output surface.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] There are many different video signals in use which are not the same resolution (neither are all of the displays), thus some form of resolution adaptation is required to properly frame a video signal to a display device.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] For example, within the United States, there are NTSC, ATSC, and VESA video standards, each with several different resolution video formats.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Multiple common resolutions are also used for high-definition television; 720p, 1080i, and 1080p.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] While scaling a video signal does allow it to match the size of a particular display, the process can result in an increased number of visual artifacts in the signal, such as ringing and posterization.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Television channels that air a mixture of 16:9 high-definition programming and 4:3 standard definition programming may employ scaling or cropping in order to make the programming fill the entire screen, as opposed to pillarboxing the feed instead, in order to maintain consistency in format.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Likewise, broadcasters downscale programming produced in 16:9 for broadcast on their 4:3 feeds through letterboxing—either as a full 16:9 letterbox, or a partial 14:9 letterbox—a technique used primarily by European broadcasters during the transition to digital terrestrial television.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] When the U.S. cable network TNT introduced an HD feed in 2004, it controversially employed a stretching system known as FlexView (which was also offered to other broadcasters).
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] FlexView used a nonlinear method to stretch more near the edges of the screen than in the center of it.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] The practice was imposed by the senior vice president of broadcast engineering at TNT, Clyde D.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Smith, who argued that pillarboxing led to inconsistency between programs for viewers, could cause burn-in on plasma televisions, some older HDTVs could not stretch 4:3 content automatically, and the quality of stretching on some displays was poor.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Despite TNT's intentions, the system was frequently criticized by viewers of high definition channels, with some nicknaming the effect "Stretch-O-Vision".
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] In 2014, FXX faced similar criticism for its use of cropping and scaling on reruns of *The Simpsons* (which only started producing episodes in HD beginning in its 20th season), as its cropping method caused various visual gags to be lost.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] In February 2015, FXX announced that in response to these complaints, it would present these episodes in their original 4:3 aspect ratio on its video-on-demand service.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Some series that were originally shot on 35 mm film—such as *Friends* and *Seinfeld*—have been converted to high-definition by cropping a widescreen image from the 4-perf pulldown.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] In 2023, video upscaling products using generative artificial intelligence were previewed or released, such as NVIDIA's Video Super Resolution and Adobe's Project Res-Up.
[src:dlss-upscaling/video-scaler] Unlike previous upscaling systems, these technologies generated new data based on provided video frames.
